300 or continued placement of video lottery game terminals.
301 Such agreement shall be on a form approved by the
302 commission. Video lottery game operators and video lottery

SB 941 21
303 game retailers shall not offer anything of value, other than
304 the percentage of adjusted gross receipts provided under
305 this subsection, as part of any agreement or contract.
306 (b) No video lottery game operator or video lottery
307 game retailer shall pay compensation or any other valuable
308 consideration to any third party for the solicitation,
309 procurement, execution, or delivery of any contract or
310 agreement with a video lottery game operator or video
311 lottery game retailer, except as approved by the commission.
312 (5) Agreements for the initial or continued placement
313 of video lottery game terminals entered into prior to the
314 start date established under section 313.431 between a
315 prospective video lottery game operator and a prospective
316 video lottery game retailer shall be invalid.
317 9. (1) To combat problem gambling, video lottery game
318 operators shall allow players to be self-excluded from video
319 lottery game play. Operators shall provide the commission
320 with a list of players who have elected to be excluded from
321 video lottery game play within thirty days of such election
322 and shall update such list periodically as required by the
323 commission. Such list shall be a closed record under
324 chapter 610 and shall not be released to the public. The
325 commission shall issue such self-exclusion procedures by
326 rule.
327 (2) Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the
328 contrary, a video lottery game operator may establish a
329 player rewards system, which shall be approved by the
330 commission. No player shall be required to enroll in a
331 rewards program offered by a video lottery game operator as
332 a condition to play video lottery games.
333 10. No licensed video lottery game operator shall:

SB 941 22
334 (1) Offer video lottery game terminals that directly
335 dispense anything of value except for video lottery game
336 tickets. Tickets shall be dispensed by pressing the ticket
337 dispensing button on the video lottery game terminal at the
338 end of any video lottery game play. The ticket shall
339 indicate the total amount of video lottery game terminal
340 credits and the cash award, the time of day in a twenty-four-
341 hour format showing hours and minutes, the date, the
342 terminal serial number, the sequential number of the ticket,
343 and an encrypted validation number from which the validity
344 of the prize may be determined. The price of video lottery
345 game terminal credits shall be determined by the
346 commission. The maximum wager played per video lottery game
347 for a single video lottery game play shall not exceed four
348 dollars. The maximum prize for a single video lottery game
349 play shall be no more than one dollar less than the minimum
350 amount required to report gambling winnings from slot
351 machines pursuant to IRS Form W2G and IRS Form 5754;
352 (2) Operate more than eight video lottery game
353 terminals per location on the premises that maintains a
354 video lottery game retailer's license;
355 (3) Advertise to the public through any means
356 including, but not limited to, media outlets, direct mail,
357 telephone solicitation, billboards, or other signage. The
358 advertising prohibition contained in this subdivision shall
359 apply to all licensees including, but not limited to, video
360 lottery game manufacturers, video lottery game distributors,
361 video lottery game operators, video lottery game retailers,
362 and video lottery game handlers. Notwithstanding any other
363 provision of law to the contrary, there is no prohibition or
364 restriction on direct or indirect marketing or advertising
365 between video lottery game manufacturers, video lottery game

SB 941 23
366 distributors, video lottery game operators, video lottery
367 game retailers, and video lottery game handlers such as in
368 trade journals or at trade conferences, and video lottery
369 game terminal operators may advertise, promote, and market
370 to players of video gaming terminals through player rewards
371 programs approved by the commission; or
372 (4) Allow video lottery games to be played at any time
373 when the video lottery game retailer's establishment is
374 closed for business.
375 11. (1) No person under twenty-one years of age shall
376 play video lottery games. The video lottery game retailer
377 shall be responsible for preventing persons under twenty-one
378 years of age from playing video lottery games.
379 (2) Video lottery game operators shall have a video
380 surveillance system within the immediate area of the video
381 lottery game retailer's establishment where video lottery
382 game terminals are located. The video lottery game retailer
383 shall maintain video footage for thirty days and shall, upon
384 request, provide such footage to the video lottery game
385 operator with which a video lottery game retailer has an
386 agreement or to the commission. Video footage taken by the
387 video surveillance system shall:
388 (a) Be deleted and expunged after the thirty day
389 period described in this subdivision; and
390 (b) Not make use of any facial recognition technology
391 or software.
392 (3) A video lottery game operator or video lottery
393 game retailer that fails to report any known violation of
394 law, rule, or regulation governing the conduct of video
395 lottery games in conformance with established commission
396 procedures may be subject to an administrative fine not to
397 exceed five thousand dollars. In the event a video lottery

SB 941 24
398 game operator or retailer is found to have knowingly
399 committed a violation of law, rule, or regulation governing
400 the conduct of video lottery games, the commission may
401 impose an administrative fine not to exceed five thousand
402 dollars, suspend such video lottery game operator's or
403 retailer's license for up to thirty days or, in the case of
404 repeated violations, revoke such operator's or retailer's
405 license for a period of one year.
406 (4) A video lottery game operator shall post a sign in
407 a conspicuous location where such video lottery game
408 terminals are located containing, in red lettering at least
409 one-half inch high on a white background, a telephone
410 contact number (1-888-BETSOFF) for the problem gambling
411 helpline.
412 (5) Pursuant to rules adopted by the commission, a
413 video lottery game operator shall be responsible for:
414 (a) Payments to winning players;
415 (b) Collecting all funds from video lottery game
416 terminals;
417 (c) Depositing all funds so collected into a separate
418 bank account maintained by the video lottery terminal
419 operator to allow for electronic fund transfers by the
420 commission on a monthly basis all applicable adjusted gross
421 gaming tax; and
422 (d) After such transfer by the commission, remitting
423 to the video lottery game retailer its share of net terminal
424 income on not less than a monthly basis. The video lottery
425 game operator may thereafter transfer its share of net
426 terminal income to its business operations account.
427 (6) A video lottery game retailer or operator shall
428 place a conspicuous warning label or sticker on each gaming
429 machine at each retail location in red lettering at least

SB 941 25
430 one-half inch high on a white background that reads,
431 "WARNING: GAMBLING CAN BE ADDICTIVE".
432 12. The adjusted gross gaming revenue tax shall be
433 imposed on adjusted gross gaming revenue. Video lottery
434 terminal operators shall collect and remit the adjusted
435 gross gaming revenue tax, which shall be deposited in the
436 state lottery fund pursuant to rules adopted by the
437 commission. The commission shall use and transmit such
438 funds as follows:
439 (1) The commission shall retain an amount necessary to
440 cover any administrative expenses that are not covered by
441 reimbursements from video lottery game operators, less the
442 amount to be distributed pursuant to subdivision (2) of this
443 section, which shall not be considered state revenues and
444 such funds shall not be deposited into the state lottery
445 fund;
446 (2) The commission shall adopt rules to identify the
447 location, by city and county, of each video lottery terminal
448 being operated in the state and connected to the central
449 control system. Such city or county so identified shall
450 receive ten percent of the gross gaming revenue tax
451 collected and remitted on the adjusted gross gaming revenue
452 generated by those video lottery terminals located within
453 the jurisdiction of such identified city or county for use
454 in providing services necessary for the safety of the public
455 visiting a video lottery terminal retailer's location. All
456 revenue owed to such city or county shall be deposited and
457 distributed to such city or county in accordance with rules
458 adopted by the commission. Any such revenues distributed to
459 the governing bodies of any city or county shall not be
460 considered state funds and shall be deposited in such city

SB 941 26
461 or county's general revenue fund to be expended as provided
462 for in this section;
463 (3) All remaining funds not allocated for
464 administrative expenses or not designated as state revenue
465 pursuant to subdivision (2) of this subsection shall be
466 deposited in the state lottery fund and transferred by
467 appropriation to the lottery proceeds fund and shall be
468 appropriated equally to public elementary and secondary
469 education and public institutions of higher learning with an
470 emphasis on funding elementary and secondary education
471 student transportation costs and public institutions of
472 higher education workforce development programs. The
473 funding provided for in this subdivision shall supplement,
474 and not supplant, any education funding otherwise
475 appropriated by the general assembly.
476 13. All revenues received by the commission from
477 license fees and any reimbursements associated with the
478 administration of the provisions of sections 313.425 to
479 313.437, and all interest earned thereon, shall be
480 considered administrative expenses and shall be deposited in
481 the state lottery fund. Moneys deposited into the state
482 lottery fund from license fees and any reimbursements of
483 commission administrative expenses to administer sections
484 313.425 to 313.437 shall be considered administrative
485 expenses and shall not be considered net proceeds under
486 Article III, Section 39(b) of the Constitution of Missouri.
487 Subject to appropriation, up to one percent of such license
488 fees shall be deposited to the credit of the compulsive
489 gamblers fund created under section 313.842. The remainder
490 of the moneys deposited in the state lottery fund from video
491 lottery game license fees and any reimbursements of
492 commission administrative expenses to enforce sections

SB 941 27
493 313.425 to 313.437 shall be used for administrative expenses
494 associated with supervising and enforcing the provisions of
495 sections 313.425 to 313.437.
496 14. The commission shall contract with a state law
497 enforcement entity to assist in conducting background
498 investigations of video lottery game license applicants, and
499 for the enforcement of sections 313.425 to 313.437.
500 15. A video lottery game licensee found to have
501 violated sections 313.425 to 313.437 may appeal such finding
502 directly to a circuit court of competent jurisdiction.
503 Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the contrary,
504 there is no requirement to exhaust any administrative
505 remedies.
506 16. The commission shall adopt rules for the
507 implementation of the video lottery game system authorized
508 under sections 313.425 to 313.437 including, but not limited
509 to, a reasonable designation of an area within a video
510 lottery game retailer's premises as the gaming area that is
511 distinct and divided from the primary business operation
512 area of the retailers establishment where all video lottery
513 terminals and ancillary equipment shall be placed and
514 operated and all gaming activity shall be conducted. Any
515 rule or portion of a rule, as that term is defined in
516 section 536.010, that is created under the authority
517 delegated in this section shall become effective only if it
518 complies with and is subject to all of the provisions of
519 chapter 536 and, if applicable, section 536.028. This
520 section and chapter 536 are nonseverable and if any of the
521 powers vested with the general assembly pursuant to chapter
522 536 to review, to delay the effective date, or to disapprove
523 and annul a rule are subsequently held unconstitutional,

SB 941 28
524 then the grant of rulemaking authority and any rule proposed
525 or adopted after August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
1 313.431. In order to expedite the orderly
2 implementation of the video lottery game system authorized
3 under sections 313.425 to 313.437, the commission shall:
